WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.494 --> 00:00:03.744
(bright chiming music)

2
00:00:07.920 --> 00:00:09.480
<v David>Dr. Conner is back,</v>

3
00:00:09.480 --> 00:00:11.100
and we're gonna turn our ascension

4
00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:14.430
to Pulmonary Number Two, and we're gonna discuss asthma.

5
00:00:14.430 --> 00:00:15.510
Thank you, Shawn.
<v ->Thank you, David.</v>

6
00:00:15.510 --> 00:00:17.160
So we're back with the discussion

7
00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:18.900
of obstructive illnesses.

8
00:00:18.900 --> 00:00:21.870
So now we're going to talk about asthma.

9
00:00:21.870 --> 00:00:24.840
What's new in asthma?

10
00:00:24.840 --> 00:00:26.550
Everything is new.

11
00:00:26.550 --> 00:00:29.400
So the last time they gave us asthma guidelines,

12
00:00:29.400 --> 00:00:31.020
do y'all remember?

13
00:00:31.020 --> 00:00:32.790
2007.

14
00:00:32.790 --> 00:00:37.260
So we've been waiting with bated breath for all these years.

15
00:00:37.260 --> 00:00:40.290
17 years later, they finally gave us updates.

16
00:00:40.290 --> 00:00:44.280
Now, so the NIH in 2020 updated the asthma guidelines.

17
00:00:44.280 --> 00:00:46.743
So the expert panel focused group,

18
00:00:48.120 --> 00:00:49.900
the same people

19
00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:55.560
work with the World Health Organization and created GINA.

20
00:00:55.560 --> 00:00:57.930
How many are familiar with GINA guidelines?

21
00:00:57.930 --> 00:01:00.240
GINA are the same people at GOLD.

22
00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:04.770
So the Global Obstructive Lung Disease group

23
00:01:04.770 --> 00:01:07.500
that we talked about last time, it's the same with GINA.

24
00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:10.410
GINA stands for Global Initiative for Asthma.

25
00:01:10.410 --> 00:01:12.630
So it's the NIH people in conjunction

26
00:01:12.630 --> 00:01:14.400
with the World Health Organization.

27
00:01:14.400 --> 00:01:17.640
They both gave us new updates in 2020

28
00:01:17.640 --> 00:01:21.060
and everything has changed except for diagnosis.

29
00:01:21.060 --> 00:01:23.580
So I underline management under guidelines

30
00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:26.370
because diagnosis has not changed.

31
00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:28.410
So that part at least is easy.

32
00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:29.640
So let's dive in.

33
00:01:29.640 --> 00:01:33.810
Asthma physiology, of course, lots of inflammation here.

34
00:01:33.810 --> 00:01:37.080
Way back in the day, we used to think this was a disease

35
00:01:37.080 --> 00:01:38.400
of bronchoconstriction.

36
00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:41.850
Now we know how much inflammation plays a role.

37
00:01:41.850 --> 00:01:45.480
So keep that in mind with your asthma patients.

38
00:01:45.480 --> 00:01:48.540
That's why, you know, David was joking about the steroids.

39
00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:49.860
With respiratory medicine,

40
00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:52.890
particularly obstructive illnesses,

41
00:01:52.890 --> 00:01:55.090
steroids are almost always the right answer.

42
00:01:56.430 --> 00:01:58.680
So your asthma symptoms are intermittent and recurrent.

43
00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:01.440
They come and go, you know, in between exacerbations

44
00:02:01.440 --> 00:02:03.090
the patient may be normal,

45
00:02:03.090 --> 00:02:05.430
asymptomatic and abnormal lung function.

46
00:02:05.430 --> 00:02:07.410
Of course, cough and wheezing,

47
00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:09.000
dyspnea are common symptoms,

48
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:10.710
exacerbations and triggers,

49
00:02:10.710 --> 00:02:13.170
which can be seasonal or perennial.

50
00:02:13.170 --> 00:02:16.170
Common asthma triggers upper respiratory infections,

51
00:02:16.170 --> 00:02:18.330
environmental insults,

52
00:02:18.330 --> 00:02:20.220
medications, and other illnesses.

53
00:02:20.220 --> 00:02:22.353
Again, don't forget about GERD.

54
00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:25.710
Okay, our first question.

55
00:02:25.710 --> 00:02:29.550
So we have a 12-year-old who's brought into your office

56
00:02:29.550 --> 00:02:30.930
for a well visit.

57
00:02:30.930 --> 00:02:33.030
Their parents report, they have nighttime cough

58
00:02:33.030 --> 00:02:35.070
and wheezing for the past several months.

59
00:02:35.070 --> 00:02:37.500
They deny chest pain and are otherwise healthy

60
00:02:37.500 --> 00:02:39.243
and up-to-date on immunizations,

61
00:02:40.080 --> 00:02:42.090
physical exam is unremarkable.

62
00:02:42.090 --> 00:02:44.100
Which one of the following tests would be most

63
00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:46.380
appropriate at this time?

64
00:02:46.380 --> 00:02:48.840
So we have a 12-year-old with several months

65
00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:50.280
of nighttime cough and wheezing.

66
00:02:50.280 --> 00:02:52.770
Would we do A allergy testing,

67
00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:57.770
B, a chest x-ray, C fractional exhaled nitric oxide,

68
00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:01.473
also known as pheno or D spirometry?

69
00:03:06.930 --> 00:03:09.330
Good, 92% of you got the correct answer spirometry.

70
00:03:09.330 --> 00:03:10.980
So that's how we diagnosed obstructive illnesses

71
00:03:10.980 --> 00:03:12.120
like asthma and COPD.

72
00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:14.400
Spirometry is the way to go here.

73
00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:19.400
Now I will say maybe if the patient was two years old,

74
00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:21.210
I might think of, you know,

75
00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:22.560
an inhaled foreign body or something,

76
00:03:22.560 --> 00:03:24.560
but a 12-year-old it would be different.

77
00:03:25.740 --> 00:03:28.410
Alright, so how do we make the diagnosis of asthma?

78
00:03:28.410 --> 00:03:29.370
Well, we talk to the patient.

79
00:03:29.370 --> 00:03:32.010
We verify a history of variable

80
00:03:32.010 --> 00:03:34.080
and intermittent respiratory symptoms.

81
00:03:34.080 --> 00:03:38.040
We document that airflow obstruction with spirometry,

82
00:03:38.040 --> 00:03:40.710
which we use in order to make the diagnosis

83
00:03:40.710 --> 00:03:42.630
to assess the level of severity

84
00:03:42.630 --> 00:03:44.130
based on impairment and risk.

85
00:03:44.130 --> 00:03:46.710
That hasn't changed since 2007,

86
00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:48.423
and to exclude alternate causes.

87
00:03:49.350 --> 00:03:51.780
Our friends at choosing wisely say we should not diagnose

88
00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:54.930
or manage asthma without spirometry.

89
00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:55.893
And I would agree.

90
00:03:56.850 --> 00:03:58.620
Unless the patient's under five,

91
00:03:58.620 --> 00:03:59.940
in which case you're gonna go ahead and treat

92
00:03:59.940 --> 00:04:02.493
because they can't do the spirometry.

93
00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:05.790
So this is the recommended test.

94
00:04:05.790 --> 00:04:08.700
You may want to do other specific tests

95
00:04:08.700 --> 00:04:10.290
based on each individual patient.

96
00:04:10.290 --> 00:04:12.360
That could include allergy testing.

97
00:04:12.360 --> 00:04:13.920
If you're unsure of the diagnosis,

98
00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:15.300
you might do a pheno level.

99
00:04:15.300 --> 00:04:18.300
Pheno is, how many of are familiar with pheno levels?

100
00:04:18.300 --> 00:04:21.570
So this is an evolving trend in respiratory

101
00:04:21.570 --> 00:04:22.950
medicine to look for inflammation.

102
00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:25.950
So if you're not sure, you could do a pheno level.

103
00:04:25.950 --> 00:04:29.913
And higher levels are consistent with elevated inflammation.

104
00:04:32.760 --> 00:04:34.440
Next question.

105
00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:36.450
Same case.

106
00:04:36.450 --> 00:04:39.240
When performing a spirometry on your 12-year-old

107
00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:40.170
wheezing patient,

108
00:04:40.170 --> 00:04:42.690
after the administration of a bronchodilator,

109
00:04:42.690 --> 00:04:45.630
what percentage of airway reversibility

110
00:04:45.630 --> 00:04:48.090
and change in FEV1 is consistent

111
00:04:48.090 --> 00:04:49.653
with the diagnosis of asthma?

112
00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:52.620
Here we go again with these number questions.

113
00:04:52.620 --> 00:04:54.090
I hate them.

114
00:04:54.090 --> 00:04:56.550
Is it A, 12% in 500 milliliters?

115
00:04:56.550 --> 00:05:00.570
Is it B, 25% in 200 milliliters?

116
00:05:00.570 --> 00:05:03.990
Is it C, 12% in 200 milliliters

117
00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:07.590
or D, 18% and 100 milliliters?

118
00:05:07.590 --> 00:05:09.720
Now let me see, can I sleuth this one out?

119
00:05:09.720 --> 00:05:11.940
Well, maybe.

120
00:05:11.940 --> 00:05:14.483
A and C both have 12%,

121
00:05:15.780 --> 00:05:20.780
B and C both have 200 milliliters.

122
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:22.400
What do they have in common?

123
00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:29.925
C, which is the right answer?

124
00:05:29.925 --> 00:05:31.353
Woo, we got lucky.

125
00:05:32.640 --> 00:05:33.930
Do try to memorize these numbers.

126
00:05:33.930 --> 00:05:34.950
However, because you never know

127
00:05:34.950 --> 00:05:36.060
how the boards are gonna ask them.

128
00:05:36.060 --> 00:05:38.820
They may not give you something as easy as I did.

129
00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:41.370
So your asthma diagnosis with spirometry,

130
00:05:41.370 --> 00:05:42.990
you're gonna see an FEV1 decrease

131
00:05:42.990 --> 00:05:44.700
to less than 80% of predicted.

132
00:05:44.700 --> 00:05:46.410
And you're gonna get reversibility

133
00:05:46.410 --> 00:05:51.410
after a bronchodilator by 12% and 200 milliliters.

134
00:05:52.860 --> 00:05:56.220
Those are the numbers to memorize for the boards.

135
00:05:56.220 --> 00:05:59.193
Increase by 12% and 200 ml.

136
00:06:01.835 --> 00:06:03.963
Here's your spirometric values.

137
00:06:04.830 --> 00:06:08.040
Here's your tracing that I showed you before with COPD,

138
00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:10.050
that FEV1 because of obstruction

139
00:06:10.050 --> 00:06:11.490
is gonna be hard to get out.

140
00:06:11.490 --> 00:06:13.680
And then there's your flow volume curve.

141
00:06:13.680 --> 00:06:14.760
Your differential.

142
00:06:14.760 --> 00:06:17.610
You know, anything else that can cause wheezing.

143
00:06:17.610 --> 00:06:19.080
What do they teach us in medical school?

144
00:06:19.080 --> 00:06:22.590
All that wheezes is not asthma, right?

145
00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:24.060
Lots of other things can happen here.

146
00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:27.390
In younger kids, it could be upper respiratory infections.

147
00:06:27.390 --> 00:06:29.430
Upper respiratory cough syndrome.

148
00:06:29.430 --> 00:06:32.100
That's that throat clearing from sinus drainage.

149
00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:34.140
It could be an inhaled foreign body.

150
00:06:34.140 --> 00:06:37.713
It could certainly be gastroesophageal reflux disease.

151
00:06:39.120 --> 00:06:40.890
Older kids.

152
00:06:40.890 --> 00:06:42.750
Think about Alpha-1 antitrypsin deficiency,

153
00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:44.730
if they're a young adult.

154
00:06:44.730 --> 00:06:46.620
COPD, if they're older,

155
00:06:46.620 --> 00:06:48.240
cardiac failure emboli.

156
00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:50.433
And again, don't forget about tuberculosis.

157
00:06:51.390 --> 00:06:53.880
Asthma diagnosis in other contexts.

158
00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:55.803
Occupational asthma is a big deal.

159
00:06:56.640 --> 00:06:59.430
Pregnant women should all be evaluated.

160
00:06:59.430 --> 00:07:02.100
The elderly, they often go undiagnosed.

161
00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:06.540
You may think that it's only you know their CHF or ischemia,

162
00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:09.240
but maybe some of their symptoms are coming from COPD.

163
00:07:10.980 --> 00:07:13.320
Smokers and ex-smokers we'll talk about the, well,

164
00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:16.140
we already, no, we will talk about the asthma

165
00:07:16.140 --> 00:07:17.850
COPD overlap syndrome.

166
00:07:17.850 --> 00:07:20.460
Athletes have exercise induced bronchoconstriction.

167
00:07:20.460 --> 00:07:22.620
And then these patients with persistent cough,

168
00:07:22.620 --> 00:07:24.870
which we'll talk about this afternoon.

169
00:07:24.870 --> 00:07:26.310
You know they don't have asthma,

170
00:07:26.310 --> 00:07:27.900
they don't have COPD, but they're coughing.

171
00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:30.630
Is it sinus drainage down?

172
00:07:30.630 --> 00:07:33.150
Is it reflex up?

173
00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:35.133
It's an interesting discussion.

174
00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:37.530
This hasn't changed either.

175
00:07:37.530 --> 00:07:40.110
The level of severity.

176
00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:41.850
This is the treatment that's required

177
00:07:41.850 --> 00:07:43.500
to control their symptoms.

178
00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:46.680
So it's retro, it's assessed retroactively

179
00:07:46.680 --> 00:07:48.900
after several months of symptom control.

180
00:07:48.900 --> 00:07:53.163
That's how you determine the severity level.

181
00:07:54.900 --> 00:07:58.260
The problem here is the whole mild

182
00:07:58.260 --> 00:08:01.053
asthma category is tricky.

183
00:08:02.040 --> 00:08:04.350
GINA, the Global Initiative for Asthma,

184
00:08:04.350 --> 00:08:06.870
has recommended we stop using the term mild asthma.

185
00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:09.030
Because you label someone with mild asthma,

186
00:08:09.030 --> 00:08:13.170
but 30 to 37% of adults

187
00:08:13.170 --> 00:08:15.810
with acute asthma had symptoms less than weekly

188
00:08:15.810 --> 00:08:16.830
in the previous three months.

189
00:08:16.830 --> 00:08:19.440
So just because a patient's mild

190
00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:22.380
doesn't mean they can't have a severe exacerbation.

191
00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:26.010
Control is a different word that means different things

192
00:08:26.010 --> 00:08:27.720
to the patient as it does to me.

193
00:08:27.720 --> 00:08:28.980
Is your asthma controlled?

194
00:08:28.980 --> 00:08:30.030
Yeah, I'm great.

195
00:08:30.030 --> 00:08:31.950
I saw one of these patients just a few weeks ago,

196
00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:33.240
came in for a routine visit.

197
00:08:33.240 --> 00:08:34.073
How's your asthma?

198
00:08:34.073 --> 00:08:35.130
Great.

199
00:08:35.130 --> 00:08:36.330
You feel like it's controlled?

200
00:08:36.330 --> 00:08:37.200
Yes.

201
00:08:37.200 --> 00:08:39.780
How often are you using your inhaler?

202
00:08:39.780 --> 00:08:43.140
Patient was only taking a short acting bronchodilator.

203
00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:45.536
Oh, six or eight times a day.

204
00:08:45.536 --> 00:08:46.369
A day.

205
00:08:48.090 --> 00:08:49.350
And you think that's controlled?

206
00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:51.570
Well yes, because I use the inhaler.

207
00:08:51.570 --> 00:08:53.910
My symptoms improve, I feel fine.

208
00:08:53.910 --> 00:08:55.140
Sure, I guess I'm controlled.

209
00:08:55.140 --> 00:08:56.580
You're not controlled at all.

210
00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:57.540
So that's why of course

211
00:08:57.540 --> 00:09:00.180
we have these validated questionnaires.

212
00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:02.700
In COPD, it's the COPD assessment test.

213
00:09:02.700 --> 00:09:05.280
In asthma, it's the asthma control test

214
00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:06.810
for patients 12 and older.

215
00:09:06.810 --> 00:09:08.463
So you should be using these.

216
00:09:09.390 --> 00:09:13.260
Now we want to assess their severity

217
00:09:13.260 --> 00:09:15.150
and their control within both domains

218
00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:16.740
of impairment and also risk.

219
00:09:16.740 --> 00:09:19.080
Impairment, I like to think of is how bad are they?

220
00:09:19.080 --> 00:09:20.703
Risk, how bad can they get?

221
00:09:22.410 --> 00:09:27.050
This is the NIH asthma severity classification, which again,

222
00:09:27.050 --> 00:09:31.350
like I said, has not changed since 2007.

223
00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:32.730
You've got intermittent asthma

224
00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:34.080
and then you've got persistent asthma,

225
00:09:34.080 --> 00:09:36.060
which is mild, moderate, or severe.

226
00:09:36.060 --> 00:09:37.650
We all remember this, right?

227
00:09:37.650 --> 00:09:39.213
So it's based on symptoms.

228
00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:41.400
Intermittent asthma,

229
00:09:41.400 --> 00:09:43.230
they have symptoms less than twice a week.

230
00:09:43.230 --> 00:09:45.240
Mild persistent more than twice a week.

231
00:09:45.240 --> 00:09:47.160
Moderate persistent daily.

232
00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:49.170
Severe continual.

233
00:09:49.170 --> 00:09:51.030
Probably won't be asked that question on the board

234
00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:54.873
because this is so old and it hasn't changed since 2007.

235
00:09:56.070 --> 00:09:59.430
Here again, we talk about the risk of mild asthma.

236
00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:03.273
GINA no longer recommends that we use this term at all.

237
00:10:06.450 --> 00:10:10.170
Okay, so we have different categories of asthma medications.

238
00:10:10.170 --> 00:10:11.940
We've got our controller therapy

239
00:10:11.940 --> 00:10:15.060
and that's traditionally been an inhaled corticosteroid

240
00:10:15.060 --> 00:10:16.890
that they might use once or twice a day

241
00:10:16.890 --> 00:10:19.230
to keep their symptoms at bay.

242
00:10:19.230 --> 00:10:21.450
And then you've got the reliever therapy,

243
00:10:21.450 --> 00:10:25.803
which is the short-acting albuterol beta-agonist, right?

244
00:10:26.970 --> 00:10:30.120
Oh, well, you know, which inhaler do you use for what?

245
00:10:30.120 --> 00:10:30.990
I don't know.

246
00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:33.720
I got the gray one and I got the red one.

247
00:10:33.720 --> 00:10:34.553
Well, which do you use?

248
00:10:34.553 --> 00:10:37.293
You know, I don't know doc, I get confused.

249
00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:39.990
So this is problematic.

250
00:10:39.990 --> 00:10:41.490
You know, sometimes the patients don't know

251
00:10:41.490 --> 00:10:42.660
which inhaler to use.

252
00:10:42.660 --> 00:10:45.180
Is this my controller or my reliever therapy?

253
00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:47.820
Not every patient is savvy enough to remember

254
00:10:47.820 --> 00:10:49.560
what their short-acting beta-agonist is,

255
00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:51.690
versus their inhaled corticosteroid

256
00:10:51.690 --> 00:10:53.190
with throughout a long-acting beta-agonist.

257
00:10:53.190 --> 00:10:54.023
They don't know.

258
00:10:55.050 --> 00:10:56.550
That's why these guidelines have changed.

259
00:10:56.550 --> 00:10:58.170
So next question.

260
00:10:58.170 --> 00:10:59.340
Same patient, same case.

261
00:10:59.340 --> 00:11:01.950
Your patient with asthma had been managed

262
00:11:01.950 --> 00:11:04.440
with a daily inhaled corticosteroid along

263
00:11:04.440 --> 00:11:05.510
with a short acting beta agonist.

264
00:11:05.510 --> 00:11:08.490
So they had the two inhalers, two separate inhalers.

265
00:11:08.490 --> 00:11:09.960
On a routine follow-up visit,

266
00:11:09.960 --> 00:11:13.230
their asthma control test score was 15,

267
00:11:13.230 --> 00:11:15.570
indicating that they were uncontrolled.

268
00:11:15.570 --> 00:11:19.530
After assessing for proper inhaler adherence and technique,

269
00:11:19.530 --> 00:11:21.750
the next best step in management would be,

270
00:11:21.750 --> 00:11:22.830
which one of the following.

271
00:11:22.830 --> 00:11:24.480
The boards love to ask these questions

272
00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:27.570
where they say the next best thing.

273
00:11:27.570 --> 00:11:30.810
Now that doesn't mean that any of these could be bad,

274
00:11:30.810 --> 00:11:34.410
they want you to pick the best one.

275
00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:36.480
So in this case, what should we do?

276
00:11:36.480 --> 00:11:39.870
A add a long-acting muscarinic antagonist,

277
00:11:39.870 --> 00:11:42.480
B, add salmeterol,

278
00:11:42.480 --> 00:11:45.600
C, change their therapy to low-dose

279
00:11:45.600 --> 00:11:50.600
inhaled corticosteroid with formoterol daily, and prn,

280
00:11:50.820 --> 00:11:53.673
or D, continue present management.

281
00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:56.190
I don't think D'S the right answer

282
00:11:56.190 --> 00:11:59.490
'cause the patient is, you know, worsening symptoms.

283
00:11:59.490 --> 00:12:02.220
So it can't be continue present management.

284
00:12:02.220 --> 00:12:06.510
So we're either gonna add a LAMA, we're gonna add a LABA,

285
00:12:06.510 --> 00:12:09.720
or we're gonna change their therapy to this daily

286
00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:12.330
and prn combination.

287
00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:13.163
What do we like?

288
00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:21.960
Good, y'all maybe played the long answer card.

289
00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:23.970
I don't know, but you got the right answer,

290
00:12:23.970 --> 00:12:24.803
which is correct.

291
00:12:24.803 --> 00:12:28.590
So these are the new asthma guidelines, which are amazing.

292
00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:30.930
So inhaled corticosteroids have always been the preferred

293
00:12:30.930 --> 00:12:33.390
controller therapy for many years.

294
00:12:33.390 --> 00:12:35.400
In patients with asthma,

295
00:12:35.400 --> 00:12:37.620
they reduce hospitalizations and death.

296
00:12:37.620 --> 00:12:40.560
They can be used intermittently

297
00:12:40.560 --> 00:12:44.160
or along with long-acting beta agonists.

298
00:12:44.160 --> 00:12:46.680
And of course we now have the triple inhalers now too.

299
00:12:46.680 --> 00:12:47.980
There's a couple of those.

300
00:12:49.050 --> 00:12:50.760
Inhaled short-acting beta-agonist.

301
00:12:50.760 --> 00:12:52.350
Again, like I said, this has been the mainstay

302
00:12:52.350 --> 00:12:53.183
of therapy for years.

303
00:12:53.183 --> 00:12:54.930
Patients think they get better, you know,

304
00:12:54.930 --> 00:12:57.750
so we're just treating this bronchoconstriction

305
00:12:57.750 --> 00:12:58.740
as it happens.

306
00:12:58.740 --> 00:13:03.600
The problem is we're missing the anti-inflammatory.

307
00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:06.720
And asthma always has an inflammatory component,

308
00:13:06.720 --> 00:13:08.310
not just bronchoconstriction.

309
00:13:08.310 --> 00:13:10.380
So this monotherapy

310
00:13:10.380 --> 00:13:12.810
with a short-acting beta-agonist

311
00:13:12.810 --> 00:13:14.820
in the GINA guidelines is out.

312
00:13:14.820 --> 00:13:17.343
And the NIH guidelines, they still use them.

313
00:13:18.240 --> 00:13:20.580
Okay, so we also know that frequent use

314
00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:23.490
of a short-acting beta-agonist can have

315
00:13:23.490 --> 00:13:24.900
worse clinical outcomes.

316
00:13:24.900 --> 00:13:26.310
The boards love to ask you

317
00:13:26.310 --> 00:13:29.130
if a patient is using one canister or more

318
00:13:29.130 --> 00:13:30.540
a month of their albuterol,

319
00:13:30.540 --> 00:13:32.160
that increases their risk of death.

320
00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:34.203
So they love to ask that question.

321
00:13:35.070 --> 00:13:37.710
And as I mentioned, GINA no longer recommends

322
00:13:37.710 --> 00:13:40.860
short-acting beta-agonist as monotherapy at any age.

323
00:13:40.860 --> 00:13:43.110
You've got long-acting beta-agonists,

324
00:13:43.110 --> 00:13:46.980
but this is contraindicated as monotherapy and asthma.

325
00:13:46.980 --> 00:13:48.360
Remember I mentioned this.

326
00:13:48.360 --> 00:13:50.940
It's okay in COPD, it's not okay in asthma.

327
00:13:50.940 --> 00:13:53.280
You have to combine a long-acting beta-agonist

328
00:13:53.280 --> 00:13:55.383
with a steroid.

329
00:13:57.390 --> 00:13:58.223
Now,

330
00:14:00.570 --> 00:14:02.160
what's new about these guidelines is

331
00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:03.990
what's called SMART therapy.

332
00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:05.250
How many of our familiar with these

333
00:14:05.250 --> 00:14:07.110
new SMART therapy guidelines?

334
00:14:07.110 --> 00:14:08.490
Not enough of you.

335
00:14:08.490 --> 00:14:10.680
So this is replacing everything.

336
00:14:10.680 --> 00:14:14.130
So we now have one inhaler

337
00:14:14.130 --> 00:14:16.920
that serves as both your maintenance

338
00:14:16.920 --> 00:14:18.900
and your reliever therapy.

339
00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:22.860
I don't have to deal with the gray one and the red one.

340
00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:24.600
I've got one inhaler now.

341
00:14:24.600 --> 00:14:27.870
And that inhaler is an inhaled corticosteroid

342
00:14:27.870 --> 00:14:29.910
with a formoterol.

343
00:14:29.910 --> 00:14:31.320
It's called SMART therapy that stands for

344
00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:34.050
Single Maintenance and Reliever Therapy.

345
00:14:34.050 --> 00:14:38.220
So any of these patients at like a persistent asthma level,

346
00:14:38.220 --> 00:14:40.380
you would give them this inhaler,

347
00:14:40.380 --> 00:14:42.780
and you would say use it as needed.

348
00:14:42.780 --> 00:14:45.540
If you're feeling fine, you don't need it.

349
00:14:45.540 --> 00:14:47.100
If your asthma starts acting up,

350
00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:49.233
you might need it once or twice a day.

351
00:14:50.220 --> 00:14:55.140
If you get worse, use it four times a day as needed.

352
00:14:55.140 --> 00:14:57.090
And then of course if you need it more than that,

353
00:14:57.090 --> 00:14:58.620
you probably should come in and see me.

354
00:14:58.620 --> 00:15:01.680
But this allows the patient, gives them the freedom

355
00:15:01.680 --> 00:15:04.200
and the ability to respond to their symptoms

356
00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:06.120
with one single inhaler.

357
00:15:06.120 --> 00:15:07.800
I love this, especially for adolescent.

358
00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:09.930
How many of us teach adolescent medicine?

359
00:15:09.930 --> 00:15:10.930
How many of us have?

360
00:15:12.870 --> 00:15:13.703
Come on now.

361
00:15:13.703 --> 00:15:16.320
How many of you see teenagers in your practice?

362
00:15:16.320 --> 00:15:17.820
Yes.

363
00:15:17.820 --> 00:15:19.140
Good, same.

364
00:15:19.140 --> 00:15:22.200
So trying to get an adolescent or a teenager

365
00:15:22.200 --> 00:15:25.503
to schedule something twice a day, good luck.

366
00:15:26.580 --> 00:15:31.050
So this is a wonderful addition to our armamentarium,

367
00:15:31.050 --> 00:15:36.050
to change them from a bid inhaled corticosteroid

368
00:15:36.060 --> 00:15:38.610
and a prn, short-acting beta-agonist

369
00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:40.650
to the one single inhaler.

370
00:15:40.650 --> 00:15:41.793
Love these guidelines.

371
00:15:43.770 --> 00:15:46.350
Alright, long-acting muscarinic

372
00:15:46.350 --> 00:15:48.570
and have antagonist play less of a role

373
00:15:48.570 --> 00:15:50.020
in asthma as they do in COPD.

374
00:15:51.090 --> 00:15:53.460
Cromolyn is out because it's takes too long.

375
00:15:53.460 --> 00:15:55.110
You gotta do it four times a day.

376
00:15:56.874 --> 00:15:59.850
Leukotriene modifiers were in for many years,

377
00:15:59.850 --> 00:16:03.090
they've fallen out of favor because of the neuropsych issues

378
00:16:03.090 --> 00:16:04.530
and the new black box warning.

379
00:16:04.530 --> 00:16:07.053
So singular not what it was.

380
00:16:08.370 --> 00:16:11.490
Now here are the guidelines.

381
00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:13.920
This is the NIH guidelines, not GINA.

382
00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:15.510
They're age related.

383
00:16:15.510 --> 00:16:18.330
So you've got the zero to four age, you start with a prn,

384
00:16:18.330 --> 00:16:20.730
short-acting beta-agonist.

385
00:16:20.730 --> 00:16:23.640
If they get a respiratory tract infection,

386
00:16:23.640 --> 00:16:25.410
you add an inhaled corticosteroid,

387
00:16:25.410 --> 00:16:27.600
and then you step up as needed.

388
00:16:27.600 --> 00:16:32.600
Now in this age group, any patient beyond at step three

389
00:16:33.510 --> 00:16:36.240
or higher probably should be seen pulmonology.

390
00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:38.490
If you have pediatric pulmonologists available

391
00:16:38.490 --> 00:16:39.393
where you live.

392
00:16:41.490 --> 00:16:45.420
And you step up and you add, you increase the amount

393
00:16:45.420 --> 00:16:47.523
and the strength of the steroid as needed.

394
00:16:48.690 --> 00:16:50.580
At five to 11, it's similar.

395
00:16:50.580 --> 00:16:54.480
But at step three we have the SMART therapy option

396
00:16:54.480 --> 00:16:57.963
with the inhaled corticosteroid and formoterol.

397
00:16:59.820 --> 00:17:02.130
The real star of the show here with SMART therapy

398
00:17:02.130 --> 00:17:04.470
is the formoterol molecule.

399
00:17:04.470 --> 00:17:07.710
Formoterol is unique among long-acting beta-agonists,

400
00:17:07.710 --> 00:17:09.420
because of its very rapid onset

401
00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:12.090
of action under five minutes.

402
00:17:12.090 --> 00:17:15.930
So the only problem here with the SMART therapy is

403
00:17:15.930 --> 00:17:18.093
that it's not an FDA approved indication.

404
00:17:19.170 --> 00:17:22.230
So we're still having insurance companies kick back

405
00:17:22.230 --> 00:17:24.390
'cause they don't wanna pay for it.

406
00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:26.133
So you step up as needed.

407
00:17:28.890 --> 00:17:32.880
12 and up, same situation, put 'em on the SMART therapy.

408
00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:36.330
Don't forget about subcutaneous in immunotherapy.

409
00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:39.300
And at five or six you might want to consider the biologics.

410
00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:40.900
So it's pretty self-explanatory.

411
00:17:41.820 --> 00:17:42.930
So with intermittent asthma,

412
00:17:42.930 --> 00:17:46.800
you can get away within inhaled short-acting beta-agonist

413
00:17:46.800 --> 00:17:48.423
per the NIH guidelines.

414
00:17:49.290 --> 00:17:53.220
Persistent asthma needs an inhaled corticosteroid

415
00:17:53.220 --> 00:17:54.630
with a short-acting beta-agonist.

416
00:17:54.630 --> 00:17:57.420
And anyone at moderate to severe needs the SMART therapy.

417
00:17:57.420 --> 00:18:01.680
Step up or down as needed, refer to pulmonology as needed.

418
00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:04.020
Here's some options for severe asthma.

419
00:18:04.020 --> 00:18:06.520
I don't think they'll ask you these on the boards.

420
00:18:07.710 --> 00:18:09.300
Our friends at Choosing Wisely say

421
00:18:09.300 --> 00:18:11.820
that we should avoid stepping up asthma therapy,

422
00:18:11.820 --> 00:18:12.900
adding new drugs

423
00:18:12.900 --> 00:18:15.750
or going to a higher dose without first

424
00:18:15.750 --> 00:18:19.200
assessing adherence, appropriateness of device,

425
00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:22.140
and technique with current asthma medications.

426
00:18:22.140 --> 00:18:25.110
So it's very important if they ask you on the boards,

427
00:18:25.110 --> 00:18:27.570
always assess their inhaler technique

428
00:18:27.570 --> 00:18:29.283
before making any other changes.

429
00:18:30.810 --> 00:18:33.120
This is a very important slide.

430
00:18:33.120 --> 00:18:34.980
They love to ask these on the boards.

431
00:18:34.980 --> 00:18:38.640
Risk factors for poor outcomes with asthma.

432
00:18:38.640 --> 00:18:41.100
High use of the short-acting beta-agonist,

433
00:18:41.100 --> 00:18:42.480
more than one canister a month.

434
00:18:42.480 --> 00:18:45.840
As I mentioned, they love that question on the boards.

435
00:18:45.840 --> 00:18:48.573
Exposure to cigarette smoking, yes,

436
00:18:50.130 --> 00:18:54.000
and maybe other inflammatory markers.

437
00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:57.753
But especially the overusing, the short-acting beta-agonist.

438
00:18:58.650 --> 00:18:59.790
Now your monitoring,

439
00:18:59.790 --> 00:19:01.170
you bring 'em back, see how they're doing.

440
00:19:01.170 --> 00:19:04.230
Follow up visits should be every couple of months.

441
00:19:04.230 --> 00:19:06.630
If a patient's really well-controlled and stable,

442
00:19:06.630 --> 00:19:08.820
I usually like to see 'em every six months.

443
00:19:08.820 --> 00:19:09.780
I'm from Detroit.

444
00:19:09.780 --> 00:19:12.330
So with our allergy season, I like to see patients

445
00:19:12.330 --> 00:19:13.470
in the spring and the fall.

446
00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:15.840
That's typically when my patients get into trouble.

447
00:19:15.840 --> 00:19:17.250
So every six months is fine.

448
00:19:17.250 --> 00:19:19.440
You assess their technique.

449
00:19:19.440 --> 00:19:21.960
Your measurements of control are the same as the severity.

450
00:19:21.960 --> 00:19:24.840
Those are the asthma control test questionnaires.

451
00:19:24.840 --> 00:19:26.703
And then you go up or down as needed.

452
00:19:27.690 --> 00:19:31.350
With the SMART therapy, you give the patient the permission

453
00:19:31.350 --> 00:19:32.970
to kind of do some of this on their own.

454
00:19:32.970 --> 00:19:35.760
And that's the day-to-day adjustment that they can do.

455
00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:39.090
There's also short-term step up where you increase

456
00:19:39.090 --> 00:19:42.090
the frequency of the strength of the inhaled corticosteroid

457
00:19:42.090 --> 00:19:45.063
and then a sustained follow up as well.

458
00:19:46.530 --> 00:19:47.610
Stepping down.

459
00:19:47.610 --> 00:19:49.110
If they're doing very well,

460
00:19:49.110 --> 00:19:51.560
you could consider stepping down their treatment.

461
00:19:52.650 --> 00:19:56.880
The Symbicort, which is the brand name

462
00:19:58.590 --> 00:20:01.950
for the budesonide and formoderol,

463
00:20:01.950 --> 00:20:02.910
it comes in two strengths.

464
00:20:02.910 --> 00:20:05.160
It comes in 80 milligrams or 160.

465
00:20:05.160 --> 00:20:06.330
So you could, if they were on 160,

466
00:20:06.330 --> 00:20:08.670
you could step 'em down to the 80,

467
00:20:08.670 --> 00:20:10.470
if you were doing SMART therapy.

468
00:20:10.470 --> 00:20:12.270
Be sure that the time is appropriate.

469
00:20:12.270 --> 00:20:14.310
You don't want them traveling, you don't want them pregnant,

470
00:20:14.310 --> 00:20:15.660
you don't want them in their

471
00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:18.120
present state upper respiratory infection.

472
00:20:18.120 --> 00:20:20.130
And you approach each one of these steps

473
00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:21.240
as a therapeutic trial.

474
00:20:21.240 --> 00:20:22.740
You know what, we're gonna try this.

475
00:20:22.740 --> 00:20:23.880
We're gonna see you back in a couple months

476
00:20:23.880 --> 00:20:25.170
and see how you did.

477
00:20:25.170 --> 00:20:26.520
Schedule a follow up visit.

478
00:20:28.440 --> 00:20:30.360
Peak flow meters, we don't have data,

479
00:20:30.360 --> 00:20:32.043
but the expert panel loves them.

480
00:20:33.630 --> 00:20:35.430
Along with asthma action plans.

481
00:20:35.430 --> 00:20:39.060
So you should be giving your patients written asthma action

482
00:20:39.060 --> 00:20:41.670
plans that are individualized.

483
00:20:41.670 --> 00:20:43.320
They tell the patient how to recognize

484
00:20:43.320 --> 00:20:44.640
and respond to their symptoms.

485
00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:46.227
They provide advice on what to do.

486
00:20:46.227 --> 00:20:50.493
And this is based their personal peak flow best.

487
00:20:52.230 --> 00:20:56.010
Okay, so asthma action plans are endorsed.

488
00:20:56.010 --> 00:20:57.960
They have been proven to reduce morbidity

489
00:20:57.960 --> 00:21:00.093
and decrease hospitalizations.

490
00:21:01.110 --> 00:21:05.910
Next question, question four, same case.

491
00:21:05.910 --> 00:21:08.940
Your patients' asthma had been well controlled

492
00:21:08.940 --> 00:21:12.390
until an abrupt onset of nasal congestion, clear drainage,

493
00:21:12.390 --> 00:21:15.123
body aches, and worsening cough of five days duration.

494
00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:18.030
They're now wheezing and requiring use

495
00:21:18.030 --> 00:21:19.320
of their short-acting beta-agonist

496
00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:20.910
every three to four hours.

497
00:21:20.910 --> 00:21:22.980
Exam reveals a slightly anxious patient

498
00:21:22.980 --> 00:21:24.360
in no acute distress.

499
00:21:24.360 --> 00:21:27.780
Respiration of 18, SaO2 of 97%,

500
00:21:27.780 --> 00:21:30.600
temp of 99.4, no retractions.

501
00:21:30.600 --> 00:21:32.970
Auscultation shows mild inspiratory

502
00:21:32.970 --> 00:21:35.400
and marked expiratory wheezes.

503
00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:37.530
In addition to continued frequent use

504
00:21:37.530 --> 00:21:39.450
of their short-acting beta-agonist,

505
00:21:39.450 --> 00:21:40.770
which one of the following would be

506
00:21:40.770 --> 00:21:44.040
the next best step in the management of their problem?

507
00:21:44.040 --> 00:21:48.660
A, admission to the hospital. B, oral antibiotics.

508
00:21:48.660 --> 00:21:52.413
C, oral corticosteroids, or D oxygen.

509
00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:56.100
Remember what I told you about

510
00:21:57.150 --> 00:22:00.183
respiratory medicine and what?

511
00:22:02.760 --> 00:22:04.143
Steroids, yeah.

512
00:22:10.230 --> 00:22:12.210
So of course oral corticosteroids are

513
00:22:12.210 --> 00:22:14.060
what we need to prescribe here, good.

514
00:22:15.540 --> 00:22:17.610
GINA prefers that we use the term flare-up

515
00:22:17.610 --> 00:22:19.050
as opposed to exacerbation.

516
00:22:19.050 --> 00:22:21.090
When we're having a discussion, you know,

517
00:22:21.090 --> 00:22:23.190
amongst our colleagues, we can say exacerbation.

518
00:22:23.190 --> 00:22:24.450
We know what that means.

519
00:22:24.450 --> 00:22:26.760
But you should probably try to use the term flare-up

520
00:22:26.760 --> 00:22:28.050
when you're talking to your patient.

521
00:22:28.050 --> 00:22:31.260
So this is a worsening of their symptoms.

522
00:22:31.260 --> 00:22:32.940
And of course the management can go anywhere

523
00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:36.600
from your written action plan to come into the office.

524
00:22:36.600 --> 00:22:38.580
You know, maybe you need some steroids,

525
00:22:38.580 --> 00:22:41.550
maybe you need some antibiotics, I don't know.

526
00:22:41.550 --> 00:22:43.470
And then all the way to the emergency care

527
00:22:43.470 --> 00:22:45.620
and hospitalization if they're more severe.

528
00:22:46.860 --> 00:22:48.780
Technically this is a decreased peak flow.

529
00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:51.900
Less than 70% of predicted normal.

530
00:22:51.900 --> 00:22:54.660
Oftentimes it's just the symptom of I'm no longer responding

531
00:22:54.660 --> 00:22:56.103
to my beta-agonist.

532
00:22:57.420 --> 00:22:58.920
Pay attention to these slides.

533
00:22:58.920 --> 00:23:02.673
Historical risk factors for death with asthma.

534
00:23:03.570 --> 00:23:06.960
History of severe exacerbations requiring intubation prior

535
00:23:06.960 --> 00:23:09.060
admission to the unit.

536
00:23:09.060 --> 00:23:10.770
ER visit in the last year.

537
00:23:10.770 --> 00:23:15.570
Current use or recent withdrawal from systemic steroids.

538
00:23:15.570 --> 00:23:19.200
Not currently using an inhaled corticosteroid.

539
00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:22.440
Overusing their short-acting beta-agonist.

540
00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:24.570
Those are the biggest historical risk factors.

541
00:23:24.570 --> 00:23:25.560
Physical risk factors.

542
00:23:25.560 --> 00:23:28.230
The biggest one here is absence of wheezing.

543
00:23:28.230 --> 00:23:31.680
A patient in a severe exacerbation,

544
00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:33.270
they're not moving any air at all.

545
00:23:33.270 --> 00:23:34.890
So you don't hear any wheezing.

546
00:23:34.890 --> 00:23:37.173
That's an ominous finding.

547
00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:40.050
Exacerbation management.

548
00:23:40.050 --> 00:23:42.810
You're gonna put 'em on oxygen as needed.

549
00:23:42.810 --> 00:23:44.790
You're gonna do short-acting beta-agonist.

550
00:23:44.790 --> 00:23:47.883
You can do the metered dose inhaler or the nebulizer.

551
00:23:48.840 --> 00:23:52.020
Current data suggests the MDI is equal to the nebulizer.

552
00:23:52.020 --> 00:23:56.133
Continuous nebs are superior to intermittent,

553
00:23:57.060 --> 00:24:02.060
definitely put them on steroids, oral or IV.

554
00:24:02.370 --> 00:24:05.220
There is some role for inhaled ipratropium,

555
00:24:05.220 --> 00:24:07.833
and then the others are no longer used.

556
00:24:10.440 --> 00:24:11.430
Antibiotics.

557
00:24:11.430 --> 00:24:13.770
Maybe in clinical practice you might,

558
00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:15.810
for the purposes of the boards,

559
00:24:15.810 --> 00:24:19.560
I would say usually yes in COPD, but no in asthma.

560
00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:22.413
'Cause the boards don't like antibiotics.

561
00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:25.800
Exacerbation management, the degree of severity.

562
00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:27.210
Mild, moderate, severe, life-threatening,

563
00:24:27.210 --> 00:24:28.983
that's self-explanatory.

564
00:24:30.420 --> 00:24:32.460
You have to follow up in the office

565
00:24:32.460 --> 00:24:33.480
with all of these patients

566
00:24:33.480 --> 00:24:36.120
to be sure their symptoms have normalized.

567
00:24:36.120 --> 00:24:38.520
So a patient has an asthma exacerbation.

568
00:24:38.520 --> 00:24:42.030
I like to think of this as an opportunity.

569
00:24:42.030 --> 00:24:44.460
You know, what has gone wrong?

570
00:24:44.460 --> 00:24:46.320
Well, you know, I was fine until I got

571
00:24:46.320 --> 00:24:47.520
that upper respiratory infection.

572
00:24:47.520 --> 00:24:50.321
Okay, well you, maybe you can't do anything about that.

573
00:24:50.321 --> 00:24:51.690
You know, I ran out of my inhaler.

574
00:24:51.690 --> 00:24:53.310
My insurance company won't cover it.

575
00:24:53.310 --> 00:24:54.600
So I stopped using it.

576
00:24:54.600 --> 00:24:56.550
There's all sorts of reasons here

577
00:24:56.550 --> 00:24:59.580
that it could explain an exacerbation.

578
00:24:59.580 --> 00:25:01.233
So it's a great opportunity.

579
00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:05.190
Next question, same case.

580
00:25:05.190 --> 00:25:07.470
Your patient's now 18 years old

581
00:25:07.470 --> 00:25:09.930
and their asthma severity level is presently intermittent,

582
00:25:09.930 --> 00:25:13.680
requiring only a short-acting beta-agonist occasionally.

583
00:25:13.680 --> 00:25:15.510
They recently started training for a marathon,

584
00:25:15.510 --> 00:25:18.120
however, and they're now complaining of worsening cough

585
00:25:18.120 --> 00:25:20.430
and decreased perform when they run.

586
00:25:20.430 --> 00:25:23.340
Requiring daily use of their short-acting beta-agonist.

587
00:25:23.340 --> 00:25:25.860
Which one of the following would be the next best step

588
00:25:25.860 --> 00:25:27.240
in their treatment regimen?

589
00:25:27.240 --> 00:25:32.070
A, add a daily inhaled low-dose corticosteroid.

590
00:25:32.070 --> 00:25:36.660
B, increase the frequency of short-acting beta-agonist use.

591
00:25:36.660 --> 00:25:40.080
C, lifestyle modifications like decreasing their exercise

592
00:25:40.080 --> 00:25:42.390
frequency, warming up until the symptoms improve.

593
00:25:42.390 --> 00:25:44.970
Or D, substitute a long-acting beta-agonist

594
00:25:44.970 --> 00:25:46.923
prior to exercise.

595
00:25:47.850 --> 00:25:50.790
So this is of course exercise induced bronchoconstriction.

596
00:25:50.790 --> 00:25:52.410
That's the new term.

597
00:25:52.410 --> 00:25:54.663
We don't say exercise induced asthma anymore.

598
00:25:55.920 --> 00:25:58.710
They're no longer responding

599
00:25:58.710 --> 00:26:00.360
to the short-acting beta-agonist.

600
00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:04.680
What could we use next in respiratory medicine

601
00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:06.120
with an obstructive disease?

602
00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:06.953
I don't know.

603
00:26:06.953 --> 00:26:09.543
I think maybe it's the steroid.

604
00:26:14.340 --> 00:26:16.440
Yes, and the majority of you agreed.

605
00:26:16.440 --> 00:26:17.273
Good.

606
00:26:17.273 --> 00:26:19.560
Those of you who did the long-acting beta-agonist,

607
00:26:19.560 --> 00:26:21.630
that used to be in the old guidelines.

608
00:26:21.630 --> 00:26:26.430
But remember, monotherapy with a long-acting beta-agonist

609
00:26:26.430 --> 00:26:29.460
and asthma type illnesses is out.

610
00:26:29.460 --> 00:26:30.900
Okay.

611
00:26:30.900 --> 00:26:33.060
All right, so exercise induced bronchoconstriction.

612
00:26:33.060 --> 00:26:36.180
This is thought to be due to cold dry air.

613
00:26:36.180 --> 00:26:38.730
You diagnose it with spirometry.

614
00:26:38.730 --> 00:26:40.230
You do a before and an after.

615
00:26:40.230 --> 00:26:42.720
So before you exercise, exercise,

616
00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:43.980
and then repeat the spirometry.

617
00:26:43.980 --> 00:26:47.790
And you'll see a decrease in the FEV1 of 10% or more.

618
00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:51.870
What's interesting about EIB is it occurs

619
00:26:51.870 --> 00:26:54.210
in 90% of asthmatics,

620
00:26:54.210 --> 00:26:56.760
but up to 20% of athletes

621
00:26:56.760 --> 00:26:58.290
who don't have asthma will get

622
00:26:58.290 --> 00:27:00.800
exercise induced bronchoconstriction.

623
00:27:01.800 --> 00:27:05.640
And some newer studies are suggesting the pheno levels.

624
00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:08.790
Short-acting beta-agonists are preferred prior to exercise.

625
00:27:08.790 --> 00:27:10.440
If they don't improve,

626
00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:12.720
you put them on an inhaled corticosteroid

627
00:27:12.720 --> 00:27:14.703
or you could use the SMART therapy.

628
00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:21.210
Okay, good warmup.

629
00:27:21.210 --> 00:27:22.043
Yes, yes, yes.

630
00:27:22.043 --> 00:27:23.400
The asthma COPD overlap.

631
00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.800
There's a confluence here in patients who smoke.

632
00:27:27.054 --> 00:27:29.350
The take home message, I would say

633
00:27:30.390 --> 00:27:33.720
is you want to treat according to the predominant symptom.

634
00:27:33.720 --> 00:27:36.240
So if they are asthma predominant, if they have a lot of,

635
00:27:36.240 --> 00:27:37.740
you know, mucus production and cough,

636
00:27:37.740 --> 00:27:41.010
you're probably gonna put them on a inhaled corticosteroid.

637
00:27:41.010 --> 00:27:45.540
If they have more COPD predominant where it's more dyspnea,

638
00:27:45.540 --> 00:27:47.823
you're gonna use combination bronchodilators.

639
00:27:48.660 --> 00:27:50.010
And of course, like I said,

640
00:27:50.940 --> 00:27:52.527
there's two triple therapy inhalers out now

641
00:27:52.527 --> 00:27:53.793
and a third one coming.

642
00:27:54.690 --> 00:27:57.210
Asthma during pregnancies, a highly variable.

643
00:27:57.210 --> 00:27:58.380
A third of the time they worsen.

644
00:27:58.380 --> 00:28:00.060
A third of the time they improve.

645
00:28:00.060 --> 00:28:01.560
Sometimes they remain stable.

646
00:28:01.560 --> 00:28:04.410
But the portion symptom control

647
00:28:04.410 --> 00:28:06.570
and exacerbations are a risk both

648
00:28:06.570 --> 00:28:08.250
to the mother and the fetus.

649
00:28:08.250 --> 00:28:12.660
So we have to take asthma during pregnancy very seriously.

650
00:28:12.660 --> 00:28:14.163
We want to see them often.

651
00:28:15.060 --> 00:28:16.950
For the purposes of the boards.

652
00:28:16.950 --> 00:28:19.350
Albuterol is your preferred SABA,

653
00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:23.880
and budesonide is your preferred inhaled corticosteroid.

654
00:28:23.880 --> 00:28:26.250
Monthly monitoring is recommended.

655
00:28:26.250 --> 00:28:30.480
It is also recommended not to step up your step down your,

656
00:28:30.480 --> 00:28:35.220
I'm sorry, don't step down the therapy during pregnancy.

657
00:28:35.220 --> 00:28:38.070
And you definitely don't stop the inhaled corticosteroid.

658
00:28:40.920 --> 00:28:43.890
Don't forget to treat other illnesses that may be at play,

659
00:28:43.890 --> 00:28:47.160
including allergies and reflux.

660
00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:50.220
And always remember that inadequate control

661
00:28:50.220 --> 00:28:54.120
of a pregnant patient's asthma poses a far greater risk

662
00:28:54.120 --> 00:28:56.040
to the fetus than any medication.

663
00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:57.660
So do not be afraid

664
00:28:57.660 --> 00:29:02.660
to use medications in your pregnant patients with asthma.

665
00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:04.770
Alright, thank you very much.

666
00:29:04.770 --> 00:29:07.602
